            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 52-year-old Czech woman with a slim, slightly fatigued appearance who presents to the neurology outpatient clinic in Prague. She moves carefully with a slight unsteadiness in her gait and holds the armrest of the chair as she sits down. Her speech is clear but she occasionally pauses mid-sentence, attributing it to episodes of word-finding difficulty. She reports that her most troubling daily complaints are sensations of numbness, prickling, and \"pins and needles\" predominantly in her lower extremities, as well as intermittent muscle weakness in her legs [MEDLINEPLUS:G35]. Chronic neuropathic pain has been a persistent companion for several years and significantly limits her quality of life [SNOMED:G35].\n\n{patientName} works part-time as a secondary-school librarian in a Prague suburb, a role she has adapted to accommodate her fatigue and coordination difficulties [MEDLINEPLUS:G35]. She lives in a ground-floor apartment with her husband of 27 years and their adult daughter who visits on weekends. She enjoys reading Czech literature, attending chamber music concerts, and tending to a small balcony herb garden, all activities she has scaled back over the past two years due to increasing fatigue and balance problems [MEDLINEPLUS:G35].\n\nShe describes her mood as generally stable, though she acknowledges bouts of low mood tied to her disease progression. She is well-informed about MS, follows Czech MS patient advocacy channels online, and occasionally expresses concern about whether her medications are truly keeping the disease in check [PMID:31302591]. She does not smoke, drinks wine occasionally on social occasions, and maintains a regular walking programme of 20–30 minutes most days, weather permitting."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:58b97f37-4695-4db6-a9d5-f5700536d20b",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} was first diagnosed with relapsing-remitting multiple sclerosis (RRMS) at age 38 after presenting with an episode of left-eye visual blurring and subsequent sensory symptoms in her right hand [MEDLINEPLUS:G35]. Initial workup included MRI brain demonstrating periventricular T2 hyperintense lesions consistent with demyelination and a lumbar puncture confirming oligoclonal bands in the cerebrospinal fluid [MEDLINEPLUS:G35]. She was initially managed with interferon beta-1a, which was later escalated to natalizumab at age 46 following a breakthrough relapse [MEDDIALOG:G35:0]. She has tested positive for the JC virus antibody, necessitating regular MRI surveillance to monitor for signs of progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy (PML) [MEDDIALOG:G35:0].\n\nShe has been hospitalised twice for acute relapses treated with intravenous methylprednisolone pulses. Chronic neuropathic pain has been managed with gabapentin with partial relief [SNOMED:G35]. Spasticity in the lower limbs is treated with baclofen [MEDLINEPLUS:G35]. She has no history of cardiovascular disease, diabetes mellitus, or malignancy. A dermatology review was arranged last year as part of her DMD risk monitoring programme due to the association between MS therapies and melanoma [PMID:37966451]; no suspicious lesions were found. She has a penicillin allergy documented since childhood. She underwent physical therapy following her last relapse in 2021 to address gait instability and coordination difficulties [MEDLINEPLUS:G35]."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
